\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 She didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t dwell on it for long because she thought she heard the faint murmur of a crowd and the distant thump of loud music coming from round the bend, the familiar sounds of a city at play. When sightlines were finally established, she was stunned to see the river there clogged with a horde of flat-bottomed bassmasters, double decker pontoons, a few refurbished aluminum riverboats from America\u8217\'92s childhood, and a rainbow of inflatable tubes. It was so jammed with watercraft that people could and did walk from one bank to the other without bending the hips. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 It all seemed so dangerous, that someone might drown. With the scented smokey haze it even looked like something out of the age of flintlock warfare: a ramshackle armada drifting through the smoke of cannon fire, a frenzy of bodies and noise and bedlam, though that was only a flavor of the general feeling, because there was also a sense of organization. Here the river banks had been shored up with concrete boardwalks, with evenly spaced oak trees and dust-white rococo railings to separate the spaces. In the middle there was an old wrought iron bridge packed with people, all eagerly awaiting the fourth of July fireworks.}
