\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Deborah Wu cut a lonesome figure at the back of a crowded pontoon boat, beautiful and exotic and just twenty-seven with only a drunken geriatric to keep her company. It was just six o\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92clock, but already the old man\u8217\'92s eyelids drooped and his mind scrambled to triage his bodily functions. Trivial things like the drool dribbling down his chin were ignored so that he could focus on settling the slosh of his stomach bile. Whenever it rose and burned his throat he\u8217\'92d twist to try to vomit it into the river, but nothing but spittle ever came out.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93America,\u8221\'94 Deborah muttered to herself. The Mandarin the word for the country was \u8216\'91M\u283\'65igu\u243\'F3\u8217\'92, and translated literally it means, \u8216\'91beautiful kingdom\u8217\'92, yet the the neglected state roads and concrete pastures that trimmed every river bend reminded her home. There were sections of Louisiana\u8217\'92s Red River where cypress knees still cordoned off \u8216\'91wild parts\u8217\'92, but every two-hundred meters or so her boat would float past a derelict oil pump. At eye-level these rusted rigs actually added to the sense of place, but Deborah had seen how they pocked the landscape in satellite images, how their broad concrete bases flared up like pimples amongst the greenlands all way into Texas, and up into Arkansas. It was depressing. The whole surface of the earth was like that, all crusted over with industry. It made  her envious of the peoples of the past, that they could walk or ride for days or weeks without sight or sound of another human being, completely ignorant of just how good they had it or just how bad all their love-making and child-rearing would leave it. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Deborah didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t blame them, though. The earth had just had too many lovers. There wasn\u8217\'92t enough to go around. It might have helped if a few million or billion people could have quelled their sex drive for her sake, but she knew that was too big an ask. After all, here she was at an evening river party, concerned as hell that her shoulder baring blouse had yet to hook a single sideways glance.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab She eyed the guys on her boat as they huddled together to go over the nuts and bolts of the case. They were almost all lawyers, and they wore the island variety uniform: bermuda shorts, hawaiian shirts, and cuban cigars. To their credit, they had tried to get her involved.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Hey Deborah, what do the Chinese think about Jakub Beksinski?\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I guess\u8230\'85 they consider him a bit like Einstein.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Einstein? Really?\u8221\'94, another asked, but before she could answer, one of the more obnoxious hibiscus print shirts felt the need to point out that Einstein had been a patent clerk when he was busy reducing time and space to a single tenseless block of stuff.  \u8220\'93Imagine if Einstein had been able to find a valuable practical application somewhere in General Relativity,\u8221\'94 he said. \u8220\'93Being a patent clerk, I bet he would\u8217\'92ve patented it and then hid the science as a trade secret like Beksinski\u8217\'92s done, robbing all of humanity, just like Beksinski.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What practical application could Einstein have possibly come up with?\u8221\'94 another asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t know. It\u8217\'92s just an analogy. It could work on a jury.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It won\u8217\'92t.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It might. If we\u8217\'92re going to get them to force Beksinski to give up his technology, I think our only play is to appeal to their sense of shared humanity.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It doesn\u8217\'92t fucking matter because we\u8217\'92ve already got half the jury on payroll.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Appeal to their humanity, indeed.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 There were some mischievous chuckles before the drunken geriatric broke it up by loudly proclaiming, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That isn\u8217\'92t why it doesn\u8217\'92t fucking matter.\u8221\'94 Deb was surprised to see that he had recovered some of his faculties. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It doesn\u8217\'92t fucking matter because either way this goes, it\u8217\'92s going to get appealed. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Each and every one of them chuckled mischievously. Deborah just rolled her eyes and poured her drink overboard, because the way the little beer bubbles drifted out into the middle of the river was the most interesting thing for miles. She eyed them as they spiraled through the boat\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s wake and mixed with the propeller's froth. A few somehow survived it all to float downriver. They were her contribution to this continental drainage system, a sad affirmation of her life\u8217\'92s existence, on par with the old geriatric\u8217\'92d spittle. She suspected that even he was having a better time because a little color had returned to his cheeks. He was sitting now with a fat smile on his face and his nose in the air.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You smell that, hon?!\u8221\'94, he asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Smell what?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s law-ee-zee-annah barbeque.\u8221\'94 The old man licked his lips and pulled the nasal cannula out from his nose before taking in another big whiff of the scented air, hoping it would further settle his stomach. Deborah\u8217\'92s own button nose was unaccustomed to the spice of pound burgers, smoked crawfish, and huge vats of gumbo, so it wasn\u8217\'92t enough to make her think fortunate thoughts, but she liked how she could see it, how the smell was physical: a slight smoky haze obscuring the tops of the trees round the bend. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Is that where we are headed?\u8221\'94 she asked, but when she looked back over at the clerk, the smile had disappeared from his fishy lips, and his bony fingers clenched his bloated stomach as if to contain a caged beast. His shoulders began to shudder, and the rumbling of an old flat-bottomed bassmaster trolling up alongside the pontoon boat was the final straw. Onboard were a few shirtless kids, and they were trying to get the clerk\u8217\'92s attention by shouting up at him, unaware of the danger in which the were putting themselves.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Hey, man, we were wonderin\u8217\'92 if- could you spare a few drinks?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The old clerk tried to stifle the upward cascade of stomach acid and alcohol, but it was too much. He twisted round to face the river, and the teens all shrieked as they watched his cheeks swell up right above their heads, and their little outboard motor shifted into high gear. In a fit of drunken grace the old clerk managed to direct the blast away and into the water, a feat which left him hanging like a wet rag over the pontoon\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s railing. Instead of thanking him, the kids all laughed and pointed, and took pictures with their phones.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0  But the old clerk\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s cheeks didn\u8217\'92t flush with embarrassment for long, and he didn\u8217\'92t sulk into his shoulders after noticing how everyone stared. Instead, he joined in with the kid\u8217\'92s jeers, managing to turn them into cheers, and he kept it up until the kids\u8217\'92 boat disappeared behind the bend. It left everyone smiling and it left Deborah impressed. She was careful not to dwell on it for long, because  she thought that this could be one of those moments where the leftover unhappiness just hangs in the air until it happens upon some poor soul, interrupting their day with a sudden flood of old and embarrassing memories. She had come out determined to have a good time. She\u8217\'92d even tied her hair up into a loose bun and brushed on a dab of smoke to contour the eyes.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 She chose instead to focus on the old red brick city now swinging into view. It was a lazy sprawl of buildings, stretching out across both sides of the river with a large wrought iron bridge spanning the gap. At least a few thousand people were out and about, more than she had expected to see, and the river there was clogged with a hundred or so boats. They were mostly pontoons like hers but there were also a few decommissioned construction barges packed with people, as well as a few refurbished riverboats from America\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s childhood. Many were tied up to the riverwalk that shored up the left bank, and Deborah\u8217\'92s boat followed suit, taking it\u8217\'92s place underneath one of the evenly spaced  white oak trees whose pollen dusted the red-bricks yellow.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 she heard the full, creamy sound of an alto sax breathing heavy off of a nearby riverboat, she got excited. It was old American jazz, the first she\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d heard it live. Nearby boats even turned off their own music in deference. It seemed to slow everything and everyone way down, as if they were all sharing in a communal sense of deja vu. The feeling was especially strong for Deborah. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 It reminded her of one her Beijing daydreams. She did feel like she knew it was going to happen, that she would be here in this place, with this cool evening air, this pollen dusted concrete, that sleepy old riverboat, that Mississippi Mistress, all of it wrapped together by the swish of the drummer\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s wire brush as it measured out the sugar and salt symphony of an 8-man jazz band. She nearly melted it was so perfect, like it had all been prophesied by one of her daydreams, and she\u8217\'92d only just remembered it. The feeling compelled her to ignore the little chain link ribbon with the \u8216\'91private party\u8217\'92 sign, and hop aboard.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 As soon as she stepped on to the pleated wood ramp she could feel the rambling jazz bass thumping through the boards. All in all, it was the kind of physical, full-bodied music that could breathe life into inanimate objects, even people. The old brass gas lamps flickered with each muted trombone jab and cornet stab, and the pewter railing tingled as the baby grand marched through its modal chords. They were playing Satin Doll by Duke Ellington. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The ship\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s decorations were just as lovely. Her red-lacquered rails were wrapped in thin wires of tiny white lights, and the awning above was festooned in red, white, and blue streamers that lit up every time fresh boxes of sparklers were passed around. Like the river, the boat was completely crowded, but Deborah didn\u8217\'92t mind because the people were rich, their glasses half-full, and everyone was quickly losing their discretion. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 There was also a rumored open bar up on the carpeted second level. Deborah somehow already knew that it would be there, and so she wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t surprised when she found it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Could I get a martini?\u8221\'94 she asked the bartender.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Sure thing.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93And a shot of something strong.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You got it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The bartender set up a rather large shot of clear scotch, and Deborah downed it immediately. Then he mixed her drink, and she took a look around the room. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The whole place was a little narrower than she expected, but it was just as ornate as she had imagined. It had clearly been built early in the age of American decadence, the age when luxury railcars were attached to plainer fares and ostentatious wealth was meant to be seen, even felt, so that people would know \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91who\u8217\'92s who\u8217\'92 - before the Depression hit and ripped blue jeans became expensive, then somehow stayed so. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 At the back of the ship, the wood-worked white arches opened up into a series of columns, and the carpet gave way to wood, and an awkward young man sat there on a bench, back straight, looking right at Deborah. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab Their eyes stumbled over each other, hers darting like little black bullets, his shaking like blue-green glass, the whole exchange taking place in a fraction of a second, the speed of love-at-first-sight, or at least that\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s what Deborah thought it was, because when the boy looked away she saw him chase a fluttered breath, and that, too, nearly melted her. It made her feel like the only real person in the room. Here she was, the only Asian, the only girl not wearing a dress, the only person who wasn\u8217\'92t supposed to be there. It was like she\u8217\'92d walked into some virtual reality, and that reddish-blonde boy had been put there just for her. It was a feeling that transcended basic physical impulse. After all, he wasn\u8217\'92t very much more than cute. There was barely any meat on him, and his ears stuck out a good ways. His classic white suit and blue suspenders seemed to be the only things holding him up. It was as if he and the riverboat had been restored together, all designed specifically for Deborah, a perfect harmony of quirk and circumstance.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 She decided upon a silent approach, to sit down next to him quietly and first make sure that she hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t misread the situation. If she could catch his eye, force out one of those double-takes, those shy smiles, she\u8217\'92d be golden. But there wasn\u8217\'92t a need for any of it, because as soon as she sat down, he reflexively answered her question before she reflexively asked it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93My name\u8217\'92s Peter.\u8221\'94 He smiled.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Deborah.\u8221\'94 She smiled back.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You aren\u8217\'92t supposed to be here, are you, Deborah?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Probably not. Should I leave?\u8221\'94 Deborah took a sip out of her near-empty glass, and stuck out her tongue to get the last drop.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, I don\u8217\'92t- I mean, no, at least in this particular instance. But aren\u8217\'92t you worried about what other people are thinking right now? I mean, if it were me, I\u8217\'92d be worried that somewhere in the belly of the ship there\u8217\'92s a bouncer who\u8217\'92s heard people mumbling about a pretty Asian girl who\u8217\'92s taking advantage of the bar and a weak-willed man in the back of the boat.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Do I stand out that much?\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Deborah\u8230\'85 Deb. I\u8217\'92m going to call you Deb. Deb, it\u8217\'92s more than just your clothes. You see that woman over there?\u8221\'94 He was pointing towards a backless black dress not ten feet away. She was quite attractive. Blonde hair, blue eyed, a southern belle.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I see her.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The woman was listening with a polite smile to some old man, but she was constantly shooting sideways stares out into the crowd, each one made John jump in his seat like he had caught sight of some rare, flightless bird.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What is it?\u8221\'94, Deborah asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 John nodded. He had a clean profile, if a little bony, but his eyes were something special. They were so vibrant because they were practically the only discernable features on his face. He barely had any eyebrows to speak of, they were there but were so light that they almost melted into his pale skin. It gave him a kind of uncertain, fearful intensity.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Deborah followed his gaze as he followed the girl\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s sideways glances. She was flirting with someone all the way across the deck, with one of the guys at the bar. Deborah couldn\u8217\'92t quite tell which one.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93See, she has a kind of sophisticated beauty,\u8221\'94 John finally said. \u8220\'93She\u8217\'92s like a sniper. She sets up at a distance, camouflages herself in idle conversation, like she\u8217\'92s completely oblivious to what she\u8217\'92s doing - then bam, she shoots. It catches everyone off guard.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The blonde bombshell threw one of her shy-smiles towards the bar, and four men smiled back.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Everyone except the girls,\u8221\'94 said Deborah.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93See, when you were scanning the deck earlier with your little periscope eyes, you were out in the open, and you were just spraying bullets all over the place.\u8221\'94 The more John talked, the more his hands got involved in the conversation, as if to compensate for his lack of eyebrow expression. \u8220\'93Maybe that works where you are from,\u8221\'94 he said, \u8220\'93but guys like me, well, we like to be singled out. We like to pretend like we\u8217\'92re the only ones that matter, like, you know, \u8216\'91that girl\u8217\'92s got an eye only for me\u8217\'92.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So, you like to be singled out?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Hey, you asked, \u8216\'91Do I stand out?\u8217\'92, well obviously. And I don\u8217\'92t mean that in a good way - I mean - I don\u8217\'92t mean it in a bad way, either. It\u8217\'92s not better or worse. You\u8217\'92re just different; you stand out.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You didn\u8217\'92t answer my question.\u8221\'94 Deborah tried to find the answer in his eyes, to invite him in to be the only other real person in the room, to tease out that bashful quiver that she had seen earlier, but it didn\u8217\'92t work. Up close, he just looked a little sad, a little drunk, or maybe a little drugged up.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Look, I mean if your goal is to hook up with a warm body, at the end of the day, it really doesn\u8217\'92t matter what you do.\u8221\'94 He slightly shifted a little bit closer, so that his thigh rubbed up against hers, but it was perfectly innocent.  \u8220\'93You could probably keep doing what you were doing, but, you have to remember that your hunting technique determines what kind of prey you bag. Like, you wouldn\u8217\'92t go out into the woods with a turkey call if you want some venison for dinner.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What works on you, John?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What do you mean?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, let\u8217\'92s say, hypothetically speaking- \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t like hypotheticals.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ok, factually speaking then. Let\u8217\'92s say it\u8217\'92s a fact that I want to go home with you tonight.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Let\u8217\'92s say? Are you saying it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ok, how about this. What do you want to do with me?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well\u8230\'85\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You just want to get to know me, right?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, if by, \u8216\'91get to know me\u8217\'92, you are referring to a carnal knowledge, then yes\u8230\'85 but actually, \u8216\'91no. \u8216\'91Yes\u8217\'92, but because \u8216\'91yes\u8217\'92, then \u8216\'91no\u8217\'92.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92ve lost me.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93See, it\u8217\'92s a three part problem. I don\u8217\'92t like sex unless I get to know someone. When I get to know someone, invariably, I end up not liking them. Me not liking them prevents me from having sex with them, so it's a vicious cycle.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Isn\u8217\'92t there some bit of common wisdom that says in order for you to love others, you must first love yourself?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No. Well, yes that\u8217\'92s a thing but... see, Deborah\u8230\'85 Deb, the sex-drive for me, it\u8217\'92s like the ability to lean your seat back on an airplane.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Is it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I mean sure, it\u8217\'92s great, and you\u8217\'92re always thankful for the opportunity, but your seat never leans back quite far enough. Then you start to get a little upset. I mean, during the flight, you just can\u8217\'92t focus on what it is you want to do, cause  you\u8217\'92ll notice that you\u8217\'92re uncomfortable, that your lower back is a little stiff.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m with you so far.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You know that if you could just lean back a few more inches, well that would solve everything. But, of course you can\u8217\'92t do that. The seat isn\u8217\'92t designed that way. And, so, you spend the whole flight like this, just frustrated, thinking the whole time about your seat, and you ignore the completely absurd fact that this whole time you\u8217\'92ve been hurtling through the air at 30,000 feet in a sheet-metal tube that is somehow, through the grace of God, going to land safely on the ground some thousands of miles away.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t understand.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Leaning your seat back just a few more inches - that was your only concern. That\u8217\'92s what the sex-drive is like. That is what being a human is like. I hate it. I\u8217\'92ve even thought about chemically castrating myself.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What the fuck.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m just messing around, I don\u8217\'92t actually-\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No\u8230\'85 your nose is bleeding.\u8221\'94 }
