\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Fireworks interrupts: Almost immediately she heard a cannon shot - a thousand pounder. The first firework to go up was a thousand pounder. All eyes followed its ascent into the sky as it smashed through the clouds, finally erupting into a great, flaming ball of effervescent light, showering sparks like meteors that burned all the way down to the water. The delayed shock wave was enough to knock over the more thickly plastered partygoers. Those still standing cheered, then toasted the start of the show.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab John enjoyed imagining the radial bursts of fireworks as flowers, their shimmering petals being tugged back down like the real things. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s like a floral arrangement!\u8221\'94, he drunkenly explained to Deborah.  \u8220\'93It starts with roses and sunflowers, then crescendos into a whole field of daisies.\u8221\'94 Deborah nodded and smiled politely, eyes fixed on the lighted sky. She wondered why there weren't more voluminous fireworks that might look like nebulas, before realizing that she was too far away to appreciate whatever fresh dimensions that might provide. With enough distance, everything flattens out and becomes simple. Unfortunate.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The show climaxed with a great conflagration of white light that lit up everyone\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s faces. A small aspect of animal fear shook loose in Deborah during the shock and awe. She cozied up to John in the glow, a dizzy drunkenness fueling a concentrated sense of each other\u8217\'92s presence.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s terrible to say,\u8221\'94 Deborah began, \u8220\'93but I\u8217\'92m glad The Experiment never made it back. Otherwise, we wouldn\u8217\'92t have met.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Jesus.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Right.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Besides, The Experiment was never going to be successful\u8221\'94, John said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What makes you say that?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I know things.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Like what?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Like a whole lot of people are going to die soon.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Deborah just laughed.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I mean, I know you don\u8217\'92t care, but it\u8217\'92s going to happen in New York.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Deb, I\u8217\'92m the only person that would point it out. That\u8217\'92s why you need me. I think I\u8217\'92ve been put here to cure your boredom.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Any theories on why haven\u8217\'92t you found your \u8216\'91reason to live\u8217\'92.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t know. I just know that I\u8217\'92m depressed all the time.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why is that?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t know. I\u8217\'92m bored all the time, too.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I bet you\u8217\'92re depressed because your bored.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What do you mean?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, the brain evolved in a stimulating environment. Think of it like this: a stimulating environment is the software that the brain\u8217\'92s hardware runs. Nature gives the brain a lot of different, interesting problems to solve. When you remove the brain from that kind of environment, what happens?\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Lets see\u8230\'85\u8221\'94 Deb pretended to wonder, as her attention drifted between the conversation and the gorgeous sight outside. \u8220\'93I guess the brain gets bored?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Right. See, the thing to focus on is that, the brain literally can\u8217\'92t do anything else but solve problems. So when you don\u8217\'92t have any problems in your environment - in the absence of any real problems - your brain will invent imaginary problems to work on. It then freaks out about them because imaginary problems only have imaginary solutions - and none of it has anything to do with the real world.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re losing me.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I think that in the absence of any real problems the brain is just trying to create a one for you. We need problems that are out of our control.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ok, so, boredom is an imaginary problem that I can\u8217\'92t solve.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Wrong. See, the problem with modern life in the west is that we\u8217\'92ve effectively eliminated any and all threats that are outside of our control, so boredom is a very real problem, but I bet you\u8217\'92ve only been trying out imaginary solutions on it. Like, \u8216\'91If I could only vacation to the right place, or fuck the right guy, life would be fun.\u8217\'92 That\u8217\'92s why you get frustrated, depressed, when the reality is that it\u8217\'92s so simple. Just put yourself out into the world where real problems live, and it will all go away.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Just think about what I\u8217\'92m trying to tell you.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m sure.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It\u8217\'92s a gift. It\u8217\'92s going to save your life. I\u8217\'92ll explain later.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ok, but only if you promise not to talk about boredom, or whatever. A lunch with an agenda is business. That is boring.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab John accepted, but only half-heartedly. She filled the intervening silence with soup-slurping and plans to get the conversation back on track. She ultimately decided on a more direct course. After all, there wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t much time.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So then, I take it that you hate most people?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93John,\u8221\'94 Deb said with a dash of disappointment, dropping her spoon in her already empty bowl for effect. \u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t hate anyone, I just don\u8217\'92t like the way humans - and I\u8217\'92m including myself - are put together.\u8221\'94 \tab }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ok, so,  if you had a button - I mean - pretend you have a button, and if you push it, a hundred thousand people will die in a spectacular and epic explosion, right here in the middle of Shreveport. That would get rid of a bunch of flawed humanity for you .\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s it? What happens if I don\u8217\'92t push it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Nothing. There's just the pushing.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92m not evil. I mean, why would I push it? To make this interesting you would have to give me a consequence for not pushing the button. If I don\u8217\'92t push the button, then the earth will die, or something like that.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Nope. There are no consequences for not pushing the button.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then what\u8217\'92s the point of pushing it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s up to you. Has there ever been an instance in history where killing a lot of people has resulted in a net-positive for humanity?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So you\u8217\'92re saying that this cataclysmic event sets off a domino effect that ends in world peace?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Maybe. You\u8217\'92re the one that's pushing the button, so its your web to spin.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I need more context\u8230\'85 It\u8217\'92s too hypothetical.\u8221\'94 She leaned in, nuzzling her nose against his cheek. \u8220\'93I thought you hated hypotheticals?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab John smiles, clearly pleased.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ok, let\u8217\'92s make it a real.\u8221\'94 He then proceeded to pull a palm-sized plastic slide out of his suit pocket set it on the table. A little pocket of air formed underneath the clear film that stuck to its surface, creating a little button in the slide\u8217\'92s center.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ok, here is the button. Its tangible now. It is actually something you can press.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab As soon as John had finished explaining, Deb reached out and slammed the thing with her closed fist. She pretended to cringe in anticipation of some catastrophe, but after a few seconds of uninterrupted silence, she smiled and said with a more weighted disappointment, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Nothing happened.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, its not activated yet.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then activate it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Hold on.\u8221\'94 John picked up the device and drew a zigzag shape onto the clear plastic frame. This seemed to change something about it, because the subtle glow that illuminated the little bubble changed from blue to red. He set the device back on the table, and began to explain. \u8220\'93Ok, so, you know how I work for Beksinski? Well this is- No! No wait!\u8221\'94 John yelled as he yanked the device from under Deb\u8217\'92s open palm. \u8220\'93God, Deb. Take this seriously! This will kill a whole lot of people! Even me! Take it seriously.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ok, ok, I won't touch it then. I promise.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab John watchfully slid the device back on to the table.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You mean you won\u8217\'92t ever touch it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Of course not. Why would I? Even if a good outcome is possible, it's impossible to say whether or not it will come to pass.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then why do anything at all? It\u8217\'92s impossible to predict the outcome of anything, even sex with a stranger. Especially that, I guess. So why do it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Probabilities, I guess.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No. There is no difference. With every decision you make, you are trusting yourself to organize the consequences into something positive. This button only represents possibility. You have to trust yourself to forge its consequences into what you desire.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93John, you underestimate the depth of my pessimism. I\u8217\'92ve already come to the conclusion that there is literally nothing we could do to fix the things I don\u8217\'92t like about humanity.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So you came to this conclusion by imagining solutions to your imagined problem? And what, you just couldn\u8217\'92t see it working out?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No, John. There are no solutions because our stupidity is biological, part of our hardware. The only possible solution is if we suddenly, spontaneously, evolve. And that isn\u8217\'92t going to happen.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Fair enough\u8221\'94, John said. He almost seemed to agree. \u8220\'93I see what you are saying. You kill a bunch of humans, then who is going to come in to fill the void? More humans.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Right. The whole button thing is just dancing around the problem.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Deb, you\u8217\'92re perfect.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93But I guess\u8230\'85\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well, why not?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \tab She pushes the button. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The shock wave caught her unawares. It blew her clear across the restaurant, pushing skin against bone, bone against organs, popping everything and killing nearly everyone. Following close behind was the hellfire, that invisible flame that vaporizes inch thick steel as easily as human flesh. This blast was only middling on the scale of armageddon; just 8,000 kilotons of explosive power, with a fireball measuring two kilometers in diameter and a kill radius measuring twelve. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Miraculously, one person emerged unscathed from the from the ruin. It was a young woman named Deborah McDonnell. The aerial pictures of her standing there in the ashen plain of a once proud city spread around the world as quickly as the news of the event itself, making it impossible for the global consciousness to separate the two- the woman and the event. It was as if the city had died giving birth to her, and that she was the reason, be it god\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s will or the devil\u8217\'92s, that so many people had died.  }
