\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 2. Egbert v. Lippmann In the famous corset stays case, Egbert v. Lippmann, the Supreme Court ruled the patent invalid, though this was a patent for a product rather than a secret manufacturing process.75 The inventor, Mr. Barnes, had improved some corset stays and gave them to the future Mrs. Barnes.76 She wore them for \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93a long time.\u8221\'9477 He made another pair in 1858, which she also wore for a long time.78 When the corsets wore out, she ripped them open and reused the stays in new corsets, doing this several times.79 The Court stressed that this was a public use and that Barnes had 72 Id. (emphases added). 73 Id. at 23\endash 24. 74 Id. at 24. One should also note that in the AIA, Congress removed the provision of 35 U.S.C. \u167\'A7102(c) that \u8220\'93he has abandoned the invention.\u8221\'94 One issue is whether courts will distinguish between abandoning the \u8220\'93invention\u8221\'94 and abandoning the right to patent the invention. The Court noted that a single item suffices for public use; a use is \u8220\'93public use\u8221\'94 if an inventor gives or sells a device to another to be used by that person without limiting secrecy; }
